<exercises><title> <em>Check your Understanding</em> </title>
	<p>
		<exercise><title> <em>Answer-the-Following</em> </title>

			<introduction>
				<p>
					Answer the following questions related to the topic above and, unless stated otherwise, assume
					<ul>
						<li>
							<p>
								The dependent variable is <m>y</m> and the independent variable is <m>x</m>.
							</p>
						</li>
						<li>
							<p>
								All equations are linear, nonhomogeneous, and have constant coefficients (LNCC).
							</p>
						</li>
						<li>
							<p>
								<m>f(x)</m> refers to the forcing function of some LNCC equation.
							</p>
						</li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<task label="chkpt-modifying-yp-1"><title> TITLE </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Consider the linear non-homogeneous constant coefficient equation
						<me>
							y'' - 4y' + 3y = \frac12 e^x
						</me>.
						Given that the homogeneous solution is
						<m>
							y_h = c_1 e^x + c_2 e^{3x}
						</m>, 
						select the form of the particular solution after any necessary modifications.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\ds y_p = Ae^x </m> 
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. This would be the correct initial form for the particular solution, but not the final form.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\ds y_p = Ae^x + Be^{3x} </m> 
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. Don't create the particular solution form based on the homogeneous solution.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\ds y_p = (Ax + B)e^x</m> 
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. This form indicates the forcing function contains the product of a first degree polynomial and an exponential function.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\ds y_p = Axe^{x} </m> 
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! The initial form would be <m>Ae^x</m>, but a like-term is also in <m>y_h</m>. One multiplication by <m>x</m> resolves this.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-modifying-yp-2"><title> TITLE </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Which statement best describes the next action you should take when the particular solution, <m>y_p</m>, has a like-term with the homogeneous solution, <m>y_h</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								This is normal, move on.
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The <m>y_p</m> cannot have terms in common with <m>y_h</m>. 
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Remove the like-term from <m>y_p</m>.
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. No terms in <m>y_h</m> should ever be removed.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								Multiply the like-term in <m>y_p</m> by <m>x</m>.
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct!
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								Multiply the like-term in <m>y_h</m> by <m>x</m>.
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The particular solution should be modified, not the homogeneous solution.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-modifying-yp-3"><title> TITLE </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						If an equation has the forcing function and homogeneous solution,
						<me>
							f(x) = x^2 e^{3x}\quad \text{and} \quad y_h = (c_1 + c_2 x) e^{3x}
						</me>,
						select the correct modified form of <m>y_p</m>?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\ds\quad y_p = A x^2 e^{3x}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The form of <m>y_p</m> should be modified until there are no terms in common with <m>y_h</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\ds\quad y_p = (A x^4 + B x^3 + C x^2) e^{3x}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! The modified form of <m>y_p</m> is <m>(A x^4 + B x^3 + C x^2) e^{3x}</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\ds\quad y_p = (A x^3 + B x^2) e^{3x}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The form of <m>y_p</m> should be modified until there are no terms in common with <m>y_h</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\ds\quad y_p = (A x^2 + B x) e^{3x}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The form of <m>y_p</m> should be modified until there are no terms in common with <m>y_h</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>
		</exercise>
	</p>
</exercises>